–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 Feb 1646":"12 februari 1646","12 February 1646":"12 februari 1646","02 Mar 1609":"2 maart 1609","1559":"1559","Lochinver,Sutterland,Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Australië","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ierland"},"en":{"1559–12 February 1646":"1559–12 February 1646","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 Feb 1646":"12 February 1646","12 February 1646":"12 February 1646","02 Mar 1609":"2 March 1609","1559":"1559","Lochinver,Sutterland,Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Australia","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cunningham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the province of Cunningham in Ayrshire, first recorded in 1153 in the form <i>Cunegan</i>, a Celtic name of uncertain origin. The spellings in <i>-ham</i>, first recorded in 1180, and in <i>-ynghame</i>, first recorded in 1227, represent a gradual assimilation to the English placename element <i>-ingham</i>.","Irish: surname adopted from Gaelic <b>Ó Cuinneagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunigan","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish or Irish   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Conahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac.","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Connachaín</b> (see   Cunningham  )."]},{"name":"Conaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Fergal.","Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire) Irish (Donegal): from <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b>, see   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cuningham","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cummingham","meanings":["(1997: 117;2007: 199; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cunnigham","meanings":["(2007: 429; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish (Donegal): variant of   Cunningham  ."]}]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Patrick Cunningham was born in 1559, in Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom. He married Lady Margarette Duarte Campbell on 2 March 1609, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 12 February 1646, in Stirling, Western Australia, Australia, at the age of 87."},"et":{"1559–12 February 1646":"1559–12. veebruar 1646","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 Feb 1646":"12. veebruar 1646","12 February 1646":"12. veebruar 1646","02 Mar 1609":"2. märts 1609","1559":"1559","Lochinver,Sutterland,Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Austraalia","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1559–12 February 1646":"1559–12. helmikuuta 1646","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 Feb 1646":"12. helmikuuta 1646","12 February 1646":"12. helmikuuta 1646","02 Mar 1609":"2. maaliskuuta 1609","1559":"1559","Lochinver,Sutterland,Scotland":"Lochinver, Suther